post_text:
Dear Germanton Central School District Parents/Guardians/Community,

Our reopening plan: REOPEN GCS ‚Äì A Living Document was posted to the website and has already been updated. At this time, we are requesting input from our greater school community. Please review the document and submit any questions via email to
REOPENGCSCommunity@germantowncsd.org or via telephone to Linda Anderson, Secretary to the Superintendent 518-537-6281 x 2302. All questions will be reviewed by the Leadership Team and responded to during a ZOOM panel discussion event on Thursday 8/13/2020 at 6:30 p.m. The event will be recorded and posted to the REOPEN GCS webpage: https://www.germantowncsd.org/domain/344
Questions and responses will also be captured in a Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) document that will be posted to the webpage.

The REOPEN GCS Team (made up of 62 volunteers) and the GCS Leadership Team will continue to update the REOPEN GCS Plan as new guidance is released from NYSED, NY Dept. of Health and Governor Cuomo.

Sincerely,
Susan LS Brown
Superintendent of Schools

FOR TIME:

100 SU, 50 sit-ups, 25 pushups
80 SU, 40 sit-ups, 20 pushups
60 SU, 30 sit-ups, 15 pushups
40 SU, 20 sit-ups, 10 pushups
20 SU, 10 sit-ups, 5 pushups

SU= Single under or jumping rope. If you do not have a jump rope or you do not know how to jump rope, you can substitute jumping jacks for that movement.

post_text:
The Germantown Central School District Board of Education is seeking an exceptional educational leader to become the next superintendent of schools.

The new superintendent will be an integral part of our unique school community and our efforts to increase student achievement. The position requires in-depth knowledge of all aspects of school district leadership, from community relations to program development.

The Board is working with Questar III BOCES to conduct the search process. The new superintendent is expected to begin November 1, 2020. The successful candidate will be offered a competitive salary based on experience.

To learn more about the position and download an application, please visit our website: https://bit.ly/3g3NpHP

Residents of the Germantown Central School District supported a $15.7 million budget for the 2020-21 school year by a vote of 779 to 488.

Due to COVID-19 and Governor Cuomo‚Äôs Executive Order, qualified voters could vote by absentee ballot only.

The budget of $15,792,913 calls for an increase of $195,295 from the 2019-20 school year and a tax levy increase of 3.61 percent, which is under the tax cap.

Germantown residents also voted for two open seats on the Board of Education. Re-elected to the Board is Ralph DelPozzo with 670 votes. Allison Meek was also elected with 619 votes. Les Olsson and Ira Sher also ran with 588 and 439 votes, respectively.

Thank you to all who voted.

NOTICE: On Friday, May 15, 2020 the Main Entrance to Germantown CSD will temporarily be relocated to the Route 9G side of the building. This change is taking place to allow the construction of the new Security Vestibule at the Main Street entrance. The school community will be notified when construction is complete and the main entrance can be used again.

The Route 9G entrance is also known as the bus entrance and is located just south of the Main Street traffic light.

Visitors should enter the bus circle to access parking. A sign will indicate the temporary entrance which is the single door to the right of the HS gymnasium doors. Please press the buzzer at the new main entrance door to alert the Greeter.

Columbia County Farm Bureau
May 8 at 8:23 AM ¬∑

National Teachers Appreciation Week - We would like to recognize one of our Teachers from Germantown Central School. Jennifer Taylor, teaching for over 20 years. Married with 3 boys. Loves teaching at Germantown because this is where she grew up. She feels like she has come full circle. When the school first shut down she knew she had to find a way to reach her students. So they could see her and know that we‚Äôre going to be OK! She started reading on Facebook live. Starting with her signature saying:
‚Äú you gonna learn today ‚Äú. We salute Jennifer with all of her enthusiasm and love that she gives to her students!

May 4-8 is National Teacher Appreciation Week and we would like to send a big shout out to ALL OF OUR STAFF at Germantown Central School! We have amazing TEACHERS at GCS who deserve recognition for always going above and beyond, especially in these unprecedented times. We also have amazing and dedicated SUPPORT STAFF who work in the background to make all that is accomplished possible. Thank you ALL for being inspiring to our students and for being innovative, dedicated and helpful. We appreciate all that you do.

Sincerely,

Your Leadership Team:
Deana, Sue, Jaime, Bev, Jim & Yvonne

post_text:
NOTICE: Today Governor Cuomo announced that schools will remain closed and distance learning will be extended through the end of the 2019-2020 academic year. A decision on summer school is expected to be announced by the end of May.

While this decision was expected, it is still disappointing to hear, knowing what it means for our students, families and staff, and how it will impact the important traditions, activities and milestones which coincide with the end of the school year.

We would like to thank our school community for your tremendous support as we have navigated through the COVID-19 pandemic. We know this news will bring new questions and we will continue to provide updates in the days and weeks to come.

Germantown Central Schools will continue to provide food and childcare services, as well as remote learning, throughout the closure of our school buildings. Please visit our COVID-19 webpage on our District website for more information and resources.

Hello Everyone from KELSO and Mrs. Schassler!

We want to check in with everyone ; )

KELSO is reminding many of you what you have learned about BIG and small problems. Always remember to get a trusted adult to help when you have a BIG problem AND that when it is a small problem YOU are EMPOWERED (make your muscles) to handle your own small problems.

KELSO wants to make sure you have access to KELSO‚Äôs Wheel of 9 Choices (attached below) so you have it to use when you have a small problem.

Try 2 (or 3 or 4) of KELSO‚ÄôS choices to help you solve your own small problem!

If you can, please send KELSO and I an email (kschassler@germantowncsd.org) and share a time (this week) that you have used a KELSO choice to solve your small problem. KELSO will reward students that share a time they solved a small problem using a KELSO choice AND the bigger reward is that you solved your own small problem.

We look forward to hearing from you and we love you!

Xoxoxoxo KELSO
(and Mrs. Schassler, Your GCSD Professional School Counselor)

It's time for Clipper Challenge #3!

WE'RE GOING ON AN EGG HUNT....

1. Make an egg (about 12‚Äù) out of paper, paper bag, paper plate, anything useable in your home.
2. Decorate the egg with anything you would like. (ex. markers, colored pencils, beads, paint etc.)
3. Hang the egg on your front door, front window, or mailbox.
4. Email acole@germantowncsd.org to let her know that you want your egg to be found.
5. Go out and try and find all the other eggs Clippers have placed around our community.
6. Email acole@germantowncsd.org or post on our Facebook page how many eggs you have found.
**Whoever finds the most eggs in our community will win a prize!**

Happy Egg Hunting!!!!

post_text: UPDATE: Germantown Central School will remain closed through April 14 per Governor Cuomo‚Äôs Executive Order to stop the spread of the COVID-19 pandemic. Under this order, our school district must continue to provide remote learning, meals for students and childcare for essential workers every weekday through April 14 even though the district is scheduled to be on spring recess during that time. The state will reassess whether to extend the statewide school closures past this date. We encourage families to continue to check their email and our website for additional information.

Dear families,

Schools are an integral part of the community and are charged with the care and instruction of a community‚Äôs youngest members. Pursuant to Governor Cuomo‚Äôs Executive Order 202.4, all school districts in New York State have been directed by the Governor to establish plans for the care of children for essential health care workers, first responders and other critical professions and occupations.
The Germantown AfterSchool Program (GAP) & Germantown Central School District (GCSD) are partnering to provide emergency childcare for essential workers. Please contact the school to receive information regarding the cost of the program as well as additional details.

Respond with the following information:
‚Ä¢ name of parent/ guardian
‚Ä¢ best telephone number
‚Ä¢ name of employer where essentially employed
‚Ä¢ number of school age children (PK-12th grade) who need childcare
‚Ä¢ days & hours needed

Contacts:
‚Ä¢ Leave a voicemail: 518-537-6281 x 2302
‚Ä¢ Email Superintendent: sbrown@germantowncsd.org
‚Ä¢ Mail to: Susan Brown, Superintendent of Schools
123 Main St.
Germantown, NY 12526

post_text:
This morning, 2/25/20, GCSD Bus Route 11 was involved in an accident midway through its morning run.

Following district procedures, District administrators responded to the scene and parents of students involved were notified. All 20 students and one driver were triaged on-scene and evaluated by EMS personnel. Law enforcement and first responders coordinated with district personnel at the scene. Four students and the driver were transported from the scene to local hospitals for evaluation.

The remaining students were transported to the Germantown Central School District campus. At the school, students met with counselors and were reevaluated by the school nurse. All students were reunited with their parents/guardians. Questar III BOCES School Emergency Resource Team (SERT) responded to assist the district.

Counselors will be available to all students and staff as needed.

Additional information is available at the NYS Police website: http://www.nyspnews.com/school-bus-crash-in-germantown.htm

Today, 8th grade students met with Dr. Christopher Lindner of BARD College‚Äôs Archaeology Program in Mr. Lecce‚Äôs Social Studies classes.

Dr. Lindner discussed local Germantown history and the field of archaeology with students. Students learned about the numerous artifacts that have been unearthed at the Germantown Parsonag. Eighth grade students were encouraged to apply to participate in the BARD Archaeology Summer Field School where they can gain early college credit and gain first-hand experience assisting the archaeological digs that are ongoing at the Parsonage.

For more information on how to apply to the Summer Field School program, please visit http://www.bard.edu/archaeology/fieldschool/.

- Stay calm around Ziggy.

Each of these rules help reinforce his training and will help him be the best therapy dog he can be for Germantown Central Schools!

Congratulations to our February 2020 Student of the Month, Haley D'Souza, and Facuty Member of the Month, Mr. Hanson!

Haley D'Souza is a freshman at GCS who has favorite subjects of DDP and English, and names favorite teachers of Mr. Strong, Mr. Conte, Ms. Hilton and Ms. Spence. Haley is the Treasurer of the Student Council. After high school, she would like to pursue a career in engineering drawing and design.

Science teacher Mr. Hanson has been teaching at GCS since 1986. Some of his favorite aspects of the job are working with students every day, being around and interacting with a fantastic faculty and staff for so many years, enjoying the benefits of a small 'family' atmosphere here, and being able to offer fun science electives.

On Wednesday, March 18, The Board of Regents will create a Blue Ribbon Commission to review the State‚Äôs high school graduation measures and reaffirm what it means to obtain a diploma in New York State.

The Board of Regents and State Education Department are holding regional meetings to help inform the work of the Blue Ribbon Commission.

Meeting attendees will have the opportunity to break into smaller groups to discuss and provide feedback to the Department. Please come and share your input!

Pre-registration is required.

To register, visit: https://www.capitalregionboces.org/graduation-measures-in-ny-regional-meeting-albany/?fbclid=IwAR3P4AiDyE6szvjb34c9lgQIHT-mDkaK6v2zWDQ1yGPoPmBy5718RtseCb0
